<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 18–22" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 18 - 22. Underside of females (18 - 22). 18 a. I. l. limbaria ♀, Belgium: Comblain [- au-Pont]. 18 b. I. l. limbaria ♀, Switzerland: Valais, district of Sierre, Val d'Anniviers. 18 c. I. l. limbaria ♀, Spain: Aragon, province of Huesca, Fanlo. 19 a. I. l. delimbaria ♀, France: Alpes-Maritimes, Grasse above Gourdon. 19 b. I. l. delimbaria ♀, Italy: Emilia-Romagna, Tuscan-Emilian Apennines, Bologna, Monte Grande. 20. I. l. anzascaria ♀, Italy: Piedmont, Monte Rosa, Macugnaga, under Alpe Bill. 21 a. I. l. rablensis ♀, Italy: Piedmont, province of Verbania-Cusio-Ossola, Valstrona, Campello Monti. 21 b. I. l. rablensis ♀, Italy: Lombardy, Bergamasque Prealps, Camerata Cornello, towards Passo Grialeggio. 21 c. I. l. rablensis ♀, Italy: Trentino-Alto Adige, Brentonico, [Monte Baldo]. 21 d. I. l. rablensis ♀, Italy: Friuli-Venezia Giulia, Carnic Prealps, Barcis, Prescudin. 21 e. I. l. rablensis ♀, Italy: Friuli-Venezia Giulia, Julian Alps, Jof Montasio. 21 f. I. l. rablensis ♀, Bulgaria: Sofia, Vitosa [Vitosha]. 21 g. I. l. rablensis ♀, Bulgaria: Sofia, Vitoscha [Vitosha]. 22 a. I. l. roraria ♀, Slovakia: Handlova. 22 b. I. l. roraria ♀, Germany: Bavaria, surroundings of Spalt." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.46559.figures18-22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/439084" pageId="15" pageNumber="242">22</figureCitation>
). Ground colour of the upperside deep yellow or orange, scattered with dark vertical lines; the dark terminal fascia (when present) is generally wide; however, the upperside is often identical to that of the previous subspecies and the differentiation from it is possible only by examining the underside. On the underside fore- and hindwing with identical colour and pattern: ground colour orange-yellow or orange scattered with dark vertical stripes (a little more dense on the hindwings); hindwing without a trace of whitish radiating streaks (sometimes a streak of a slightly lighter yellow, for example in specimens from Poland and Slovakia).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="242">
On the upperside, the dark terminal fascia is variable: according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Povolny, D" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae" pageId="17" pageNumber="244" pagination="125 - 143" refId="B27" refString="Povolny, D, Moucha, J, 1957. Kritische Bemerkungen zu einigen Geometridengattungen (Lep., Geometridae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae 31: 125 - 143" title="Kritische Bemerkungen zu einigen Geometridengattungen (Lep., Geometridae)." volume="31" year="1957">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Povolný">Povolny</normalizedToken>
and Moucha (1957)
</bibRefCitation>
in Slovakia most of the individuals from the Ore Mountains have this fascia less developed than those from Vihorlat Mountains and in the first locality it is absent in a high percentage of females (but also males). In Poland (
<bibRefCitation author="Blaik, T" journalOrPublisher="Polish Journal of Entomology" pageId="16" pageNumber="243" pagination="23 - 37" refId="B3" refString="Blaik, T, 2003. Notes on the occurrence of Isturgia roraria Fabricius, 1777 (Lepidoptera: Geometridae) in Poland with remarks on its ecology, biology and variability. Polish Journal of Entomology 72: 23 - 37" title="Notes on the occurrence of Isturgia roraria Fabricius, 1777 (Lepidoptera: Geometridae) in Poland with remarks on its ecology, biology and variability." volume="72" year="2003">Blaik 2003</bibRefCitation>
) this fascia is wide and always present in the males (more or less distinct), almost always indistinct or absent in the females; specimens were collected in a locality with a large area of the forewing upperside without dark markings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="242">In the female genitalia signum large (1.2-1.4 mm). Bullae tympani without roundish lobe.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="242" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="242">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="242">
North-eastern and south-eastern Germany (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Skou, P" journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden" pageId="17" pageNumber="244" refId="B37" refString="Skou, P, Sihvonen, P, 2015. Ennominae I. In: Hausmann A (Ed.) The Geometrid Moths of Europe 5. Brill, Leiden" title="Ennominae I. In: Hausmann A (Ed.) The Geometrid Moths of Europe 5." year="2015">Skou and Sihvonen 2015</bibRefCitation>
: map on page 99), Austria (
<bibRefCitation author="Huemer, P" journalOrPublisher="H, Innsbruck" pageId="16" pageNumber="243" refId="B13" refString="Huemer, P, 2013. Die Schmetterlinge Oesterreichs (Lepidoptera). Systematische und faunistische Checkliste. Studiohefte 12, Tiroler Landesmuseen-Betriebsgesellshaft m.b. H, Innsbruck" title="Die Schmetterlinge Oesterreichs (Lepidoptera). Systematische und faunistische Checkliste. Studiohefte 12, Tiroler Landesmuseen-Betriebsgesellshaft m. b." year="2013">Huemer 2013</bibRefCitation>
: Lower Austria), southern Poland, Czech Republic, Slovakia, north-eastern Hungary. For Romania, see the previous subspecies. 
<bibRefCitation author="Viidalepp, J" journalOrPublisher="Apollo Books, Stenstrup" pageId="17" pageNumber="244" refId="B39" refString="Viidalepp, J, 1996. Checklist of the Geometridae (Lepidoptera) of the former U.S.S.R.. Apollo Books, Stenstrup" title="Checklist of the Geometridae (Lepidoptera) of the former U. S. S. R .." year="1996">Viidalepp (1996)</bibRefCitation>
attributes to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Genista" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="roraria" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="242" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="roraria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="242">roraria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. str. the populations from Ukraine, south-eastern Russia and southern Urals.
</paragraph>
